{"title":"Can LLM be a Personalized Judge?","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"LLM-as-a-Judge is widely used to evaluate personalization, but its reliability for inferring user-specific preferences is unclear and often low, partly due to sparse/irrelevant persona information.","method":"Augment the LLM-as-a-Personalized-Judge pipeline with verbal uncertainty estimation: instruct the LLM to output both a preference judgment and a certainty score on a 1–100 scale, then filter evaluations by a certainty threshold (e.g., ≥80). Across PRISM, OpinionQA, EC, and Public Reddit with models including GPT-4 and Command R+, high-certainty subsets reach around or above 80% agreement with human ground truth on binary tasks, while a tie option is rarely used and degrades utility. This makes certainty-thresholded judging a more reliable proxy than standard judging without uncertainty."},{"problem":"Persona sparsity—limited or task-irrelevant persona variables—reduces the predictive power for preference inference, and evaluators need a way to detect when the persona is insufficient.","method":"Use the LLM’s self-reported certainty as a proxy for persona sufficiency and sample/task difficulty. Conduct ablations that restrict persona inputs (e.g., using only three key features vs. a single least-informative feature) and observe large drops in both the number of high-certainty samples and accuracy (e.g., on OpinionQA, high-confidence cases drop from 480 to 10 when reduced to one feature), while confidence distributions correlate with known task difficulty (PR > PRISM/OpinionQA > EC). This enables principled filtering/deprioritization of uncertain cases driven by persona sparsity."},{"problem":"Third-person human judging for personalization is costly and variable; it is unclear whether an LLM-based personalized judge can match human evaluators.","method":"Run a crowdsourcing study on OpinionQA where annotators infer preferences from personas with the same prompts and certainty reporting. Compare GPT-4’s certainty-aware judgments to majority-vote human labels: overall accuracy is comparable (62.3% vs. 63.3%), and on high-certainty samples GPT-4 surpasses humans (79.2% vs. 71.4%). This validates certainty-aware LLM-as-a-Personalized-Judge as a scalable alternative when first-person labels are unavailable."}]}
